343","1278–1344":"1278–1344","1275":"1275","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1304":"1304","1315":"1315","1344":"1344","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1333":"1333","1343":"1343","1354":"1354","8 janvier 1300":"8 January 1300","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","Europe":"Europe","Fiennes, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Fiennes, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France","Bois de Boulogne, Férolles Attilly, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Férolles-Attilly, Seine-et-Marne, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DITE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Dyte  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dyte","meanings":["English: nickname, perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English * <i>dight</i>, a side-form of Middle English  <i>dought</i> ‘brave, valiant’, and possibly derived therefore from a shortened form of Old English  <i>dyhtig</i>,  <i>dohtig</i> ‘doughty’.  Compare  Doughty  ."]}]},{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"SAINT","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"VENANT","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish, English:  see  Tennant  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tennant","meanings":["Scottish and English: status name for a farmer who held his land from an overlord by obligations of rent or service, from Middle English <i>tena(u)nt</i> ‘tenant’ (Old French <i>tenant</i>). This was the normal situation for landholders in the Middle Ages, since in the feudal system all land belonged ultimately to the king and use of it was granted in return for financial or military support."]}]},{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"WAVRIN","type":"LAST","meanings":["An old name. The same as Waring or Guerin, who came over with the Conqueror; a name probably connected with that of the Waernas or Wernas. the Varini or Verini, a people of the Elbe"],"variants":[]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marie DITE DE SAINT VENANT DE WAVRIN was born in 1275, her father, Hellin de Waverin de Waziers IV, was 2 and her mother, Isabeau de Cuelster, was -3. She had at least 2 sons a